What is the FileSystem Hierarchy standard(FHS)?
The  FileSystem Hierarchy standard(FHS) is defines where different types of files should be stored in a Linux System

Root Directory(/)
Everthing in Linux starts from the root directory, represented by a single slash(/), every filesystem is mounted somewhere under /.
/
├── bin
├── boot
├── dev
├── etc
├── home
├── lib
├── media
├── mnt
├── opt
├── proc
├── root
├── run
├── sbin
├── srv
├── sys
├── tmp
├── usr
└── var

1. /bin --> Essential User Commands , Contains binary executables
Conatins the essential commands required by all users
Example:
- ls
- cp
- mv
- cat 
- pwd
- echo
- mkdir
- rm

2. /sbin ---> System Administration Commands
contains Commands mainly intended for system administration
Examples:
- ip 
- fdisk
- mkfs
- reboot
- shutdown
These are typically used by Administrators(often via sudo)

3. /etc (Editable Text Configuration)--> contains Configuration Files

This is one of the most important directories
It contains system-wide configuartion files

Examples:
- /etc/passwd
- /etc/group
- /etc/hosts
- /etc/fstab
- /etc/ssh
- /etc/systemd

Production examples:
- ssh configuartion
- network configuration
- Service configuration
- user information

4. /home --> User Home Directories
Every normal user gets a home directory

Example:
/home/alice
/home/bob
/home/vinod

inside you'll find
- Documents
- Downloads
- Projects
- Personal confgurations files(often starting with .)

5. /root --> Root User's Home
this is not the root directory(/).
its the home directory of the root user
/root
Only the root account normally uses this directory

6. /boot --> Boot Files
Contains files required to boot the operating system

Examples:
- vmlinuz
- initramfs
- grub
these are used by the bootloader to start Linux

7. /dev -- > Device Files
In Linux , devices are represented as files
Examples:
- /dev/sda
- /dev/sdb
- /dev/null
- /dev/random
- /dev/tty

8. /proc --> Process infromation

A virtual filesystem created by the kernel

It doesn't store data on disk. Instead, it expose kernel and process information.

Example:
- /proc/cpuinfo
- /proc/meminfo
- /proc/uptime

9. /sys --> kernel & Hardware information

Another virtual filesystem.

provides information about:

- hardware
- Devices
- Kernel settings

Commonly used for advanced system administration and debugging

10. /var --> variable Data

Stores files that chnages frequently
Examples:
- /var/log
- /var/cache
- /var/spool
- /var/tmp
This is a key directory for troubleshooting.
Useful logs iinclude:
- /var/log/sys.log
- /var/log/auth.log
- /var/log/messages


11. /tmp --> Temporary Files
Applications store temporary files here.

Characteristics:

- Writable by all users (with special permissions)
- Often cleaned automatically after reboot or periodically 

12. /usr --> User Programs & Libraries

Despite its name, this is not where user home directories are stored.

It contains many installed applications and libraries.

Examples:
- /usr/bin
- /usr/sbin
- /usr/lib
- /usr/share
- /usr/local

13. /opt --> Optional Software
Used for optional third-party applications
example:
- /opt/sonarqube

14. /mnt --> Temporary Mount Point
Traditionally used to temporarily mount filesystems.
example:
sudo mount /dev/sdb1 /mnt

15. /media — Removable Media
Automatically mounted removable devices often appear here.

Examples:

- /media/cdrom
- /media/usb

16. /run — Runtime Data
Stores runtime information since the last boot.
Examples include:

Process IDs (PID files)
Socket files
Runtime state

The contents are typically cleared on reboot.

